  "why": "The paper enforces plausibility checks for each individual mutation (a per-step validity test is applied before accepting a mutated input into the seed pool) and reports that NLC-guided mutations produce more natural-looking inputs (measured by IS/FID). However, the paper does not describe any mechanism that explicitly controls or bounds cumulative distortion across repeated rounds of mutation (e.g., tracking total perturbation relative to the original seed, or constraining search via a generative model). The validity test is applied between the current seed and the immediate mutated input (is_valid(ŝ, s)), which preserves plausibility per step but does not explicitly prevent semantic degradation over multiple mutation iterations.",
  "evidence": "Page 10, Sec. VI-B (Fuzzing setup) and Algorithm 1: \"is_valid() is adopted from [47], which deems a mutation as valid if 1) the #changed-pixels is less than α× #pixels or 2) the maximum of changed pixel value is less than β ×255. We set α to 0.2 and β to 0.4.\" (Alg.1 line: if is_valid(sˆ,s) and coverage inc(C,D) then S.add(sˆ); update coverage(C);). Page 2, Abstract/Contributions: \"fuzz testing under the guidance of NLC can also detect a large number of errors, which are shown as diverse and natural-looking. ... the mutations guided by NLC generate more natural inputs.\" Page 11, Sec. VI-B (Naturalness of Mutations / Results): \"Overall, mutated images guided by NLC have the best scores for both IS and FID.\" Nowhere in the paper is there an explicit mechanism described for measuring or limiting cumulative distortion relative to the original seed across multiple mutation rounds (no tracking of total perturbation nor use of a generative model to restrict the search to a plausible distribution is described)."
